---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'AI Optimisation Agency: What It Actually Is and Whether You Need One';
const description = "What an AI optimisation agency claims to do, why most claims don't survive scrutiny, and whether the work justifies a separate retainer or just fits inside existing SEO and PR.";

const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://geooptimised.com/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'AI Optimisation Agency', item: 'https://geooptimised.com/ai-optimisation-agency/' },
    ],
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: title,
    description,
    datePublished: '2026-07-20',
    dateModified: '2026-07-20',
    author: { '@type': 'Person', '@id': 'https://geooptimised.com/#sunny-patel', name: 'Sunny Patel' },
    publisher: { '@id': 'https://geooptimised.com/#organization' },
  },
];
---
<Base title={title} description={description} schema={schema} ogType="article">
  <article>
    <header class="wrap pt-14 pb-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="data text-[0.7rem] uppercase tracking-widest mb-6" style="color: var(--muted);">
        <a href="/">Home</a> <span aria-hidden="true">/</span> <span style="color: var(--text);">AI Optimisation Agency</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-[2.2rem] sm:text-[3rem] leading-[1.06] max-w-[20ch]">What is an AI optimisation agency, really?</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-[64ch] text-[1.12rem]" style="color: var(--text-soft);">
        The term "AI optimisation agency" has become a catch-all category that describes everything from generative engine optimisation (GEO) consulting to content strategy to SEO rebranding. We break down what these services actually deliver, what the evidence says about their effectiveness, and when you might need one versus when you are paying for the same work twice.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 data text-[0.72rem]" style="color: var(--muted);">
        By Sunny Patel &middot; 20 July 2026
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="wrap pb-12">
      <div class="border-l-4 pl-6 py-1 max-w-[64ch]" style="border-color: var(--accent);">
        <p class="font-display text-[1.3rem] leading-snug" style="color: var(--text);">
          An "AI optimisation agency" is most often an SEO consultancy that has relabelled existing services (content, authority-building, technical SEO) under a new acronym. Whether the actual work differs from what you would get from an SEO agency depends entirely on the specific firm. Many do identical work. Some have added real AI-specific measurement, which is rare and valuable. Most are betting you will not notice the overlap.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap pb-24 copy">
      <h2>What an AI optimisation agency claims to do</h2>
      <p>
        The market narrative is that AI optimisation is a distinct discipline from search engine optimisation. These firms argue that optimising for AI-generated answers requires different signals, different content structures, and different measurement than optimising for ranked search results. The services they typically advertise include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Citation tracking across AI platforms</strong> — monitoring whether your brand appears in answers generated by ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, and other systems.</li>
        <li><strong>Entity authority building</strong> — strengthening your brand presence across Wikipedia, Wikidata, knowledge graphs, and industry-specific databases that AI systems reference.</li>
        <li><strong>Content restructuring</strong> — rewriting existing pages to make them more quotable and extractable by language models.</li>
        <li><strong>AI crawler management</strong> — configuring robots.txt and llms.txt to control how generative AI systems crawl your site (though this is often misrepresented).</li>
        <li><strong>Structured data optimisation</strong> — implementing JSON-LD schema to help AI systems understand and cite your content correctly.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Where the overlap with SEO becomes obvious</h2>
      <p>
        Building entity authority, writing clear and quotable content, implementing structured data, and managing crawler access are not new. Each of these techniques was developed by SEO professionals over the past fifteen years. An honest AI optimisation agency would acknowledge that the technical foundation of the work is identical to good SEO; the difference is the measurement target (citations in AI systems rather than Google rankings) and the weighting of certain signals (entity presence may matter more than exact keyword match).
      </p>
      <p>
        The problem is that many agencies do not make that distinction. They present the work as if it requires a completely separate approach, sometimes for separate fees. This is misleading. A properly structured SEO engagement that prioritises entity authority, topical coverage, and quotability will almost automatically improve your AI visibility. You do not need a separate retainer.
      </p>

      <h2>When an AI optimisation agency is actually useful</h2>
      <p>
        There are three narrow cases where hiring someone specifically for AI optimisation makes sense:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>You already have a strong SEO programme and want to layer AI-specific measurement.</strong> If your search rankings are stable, your technical SEO is sound, and your content is well-structured, then adding AI citation tracking can reveal growth vectors your SEO data alone would not. An agency that can show which queries trigger competitor citations in Perplexity, whether your Wikipedia entry affects your Gemini appearance, or how third-party placements move citation share across platforms is adding something you do not have. The work is additive, not replacement.</li>
        <li><strong>You are in a category where AI assistants are the majority search method.</strong> For research, technical documentation, programming, or open-source projects, AI search has already displaced traditional search in user behaviour. In these categories, optimisation for AI citations is not optional, and doing it well requires dedicated attention. An agency experienced in your category is valuable.</li>
        <li><strong>You want international or multilingual AI visibility.</strong> Optimising for AI across multiple languages and geographies is more complex than SEO, because each major model (ChatGPT, Gemini, Copilot, Claude) has different training data, cutoff dates, and regional licensing deals. A firm that can map your visibility across all models and all relevant markets is solving a real problem you cannot easily solve in-house.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What to ask before you hire anyone</h2>
      <p>
        If you decide to engage an AI optimisation agency, ask these questions before you sign:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Can you show me a specific before-and-after?</strong> "We improved AI visibility by 34%" is meaningless without knowing the baseline metric, sample size, and measurement method. An agency that cannot show a specific, auditable example is guessing.</li>
        <li><strong>Is this work you would do differently than an SEO consultancy would?</strong> If the answer is no, then you are paying for a rebranding. If the answer is yes, they should be able to articulate exactly what is different and why.</li>
        <li><strong>How do you measure success for clients?</strong> If they measure success via "AI visibility scores" from tools with unverified methodologies, they are optimising for a metric that does not correlate to business outcomes. Press for traffic, conversions, or customer acquisition cost.</li>
        <li><strong>What is the overlap with your existing SEO programme?</strong> Ensure you are not paying two agencies to do the same work. Content strategy, authority building and technical implementation should have single owners.</li>
        <li><strong>Can you explain why the common pattern (silence on AI crawlers) is the right pattern for my specific case?</strong> Most firms should not block AI crawlers or spend budget managing them. An agency that wants to do this work anyway without a clear business rationale is creating work to justify a retainer.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The verdict</h2>
      <p>
        The category "AI optimisation agency" exists because the marketing works. Businesses are anxious about AI, executives want to signal they are ahead of a trend, and consultancies profit from bundling existing practices under a new name. That does not mean the work is valueless. Being cited in AI systems is worth having, and a team that understands the subtle differences between optimising for ranked results and optimising for citations can add real value.
      </p>
      <p>
        What is not defensible is the idea that you need a separate agency, separate team, or separate budget for it. If you have a good SEO programme and a good PR programme, and you are already doing the unsexy work (original research, quotable writing, third-party placements), then you have 80% of what you need for good AI visibility. The remaining 20% — measurement specific to AI, international optimization, or market-specific expertise — can be added as a project or feature within your existing consultancy relationships. You probably do not need a new one.
      </p>

      <div class="rule mt-12 pt-8">
        <p class="text-[0.95rem]" style="color: var(--muted);">
          Every quotation and statistic on this page is sourced in the <a class="link" href="/evidence/">evidence ledger</a>.
          We do not sell AI optimisation services. See <a class="link" href="/who-pays-us/">who pays us</a> and
          <a class="link" href="/is-geo-a-scam/">Is GEO a scam?</a> for additional context on the category.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
